{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507303"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:51:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:51:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2617"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.53,0.39,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76260"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61764"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"719"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3283"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76260"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of worsening shortness of breath and dry cough. She has also noticed 10 kilograms of unintentional weight loss over six months. She has no chest pain, ankle swelling, nausea, diarrhoea, vomiting, or night sweats.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and hypercholesterolaemia. Her medications include metformin, sitagliptin, and rosuvastatin. She has a 50 pack-year smoking history and continues to smoke. She does not drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 132/84 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen shows prominent dilated superficial veins with superior blood flow (Image). The abdomen is soft and non-tender with normal bowel sounds. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of these examination findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left inguinal hernia","Deep venous thrombosis of left leg","Inferior vena cava occlusion","Portal vein thrombosis","Sapheno-femoral incompetence"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with constitutional symptoms suggestive of malignancy (weight loss, smoking history) and examination findings of dilated superficial abdominal veins with superior blood flow. \u003Cstrong\u003EInferior vena cava (IVC) occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis, likely secondary to lung cancer given her significant smoking history and respiratory symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeep venous thrombosis of left leg\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with unilateral leg swelling and pain. While it can cause collateral vessels to develop, these would be more prominent in the affected leg rather than the anterior abdominal wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft inguinal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E presents as a visible or palpable bulge in the groin area that may increase with standing or straining. It would not cause the pattern of venous collaterals seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPortal vein thrombosis\u003C/strong\u003E causes portal hypertension with development of collateral vessels around the umbilicus (caput medusae). Importantly, blood flow in portal hypertension is inferior (away from the umbilicus), whereas this patient has superior flow.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESapheno-femoral incompetence\u003C/strong\u003E causes varicose veins in the lower limbs due to venous valve dysfunction. It would not cause the extensive abdominal wall collaterals seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe direction of blood flow in dilated superficial veins is a key diagnostic feature. Superior flow (towards the head) indicates IVC obstruction as the body attempts to return blood to the heart via alternative routes. Common causes of IVC obstruction include external compression from tumours (particularly lung cancer), direct tumour invasion (especially renal cell carcinoma), and thrombosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The direction of blood flow in dilated superficial abdominal veins helps determine the aetiology - superior flow suggests IVC obstruction, inferior flow suggests portal hypertension.","Lung cancer can present with IVC obstruction due to mass effect or direct invasion.","Constitutional symptoms like weight loss and smoking history should raise suspicion for underlying malignancy in cases of IVC obstruction."],"references":["Lawrensia S, Khan YS. Inferior Vena Cava Syndrome. [Updated 2021 Feb 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560885/","Bhaskar ME. Direction of blood flow in a vein. Mayo Clin Proc. 2009 Apr;84(4):306. doi: 10.4065/84.4.306. PMID: 19339645; PMCID: PMC2665972. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2665972/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61764"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15287"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15287","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15287"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/96934eda-b868-4bee-8b15-e953d2bc1708.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/96934eda-b868-4bee-8b15-e953d2bc1708.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":600,"height":409}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61764"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T16:34:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T16:34:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76260"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summa